sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1114504
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: MoClo Level 1 RFP reporter with AE fusion sites
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
pJ04B13Rm_AE

This is a MoClo Level 1 reporting device containing the Level 0 parts J23104_AB, BCD13_BC, E1010m_CD, and B0015_DE within the DVL1_AE backbone. The flanking fusion sites are A on the 5' side and E on the 3' side of the insert. The fusion site letters refer to 4bp fusion sites: A = GGAG; B = TACT; C = AATG; D = AGGT; E = GCTT; F = CGCT; G = TGCC; H = ACTA. See Level 0 pages for further information.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Jake Awtry
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Construct of MoClo Level 0 parts derived from iGEM Distribution Kits

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1114110
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Bicistronic design RBS 13, MoClo Format with BC fusion sites
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the MoClo formatted part of a bicistronic design ribosomal binding site 13 with BC fusion sites. This is a Level 0 MoClo part with flanking sites B on the 5' side and site C on the 3' side of the part. The fusion site letters refer to 4bp fusion sites: A = GGAG; B = TACT; C = AATG; D = AGGT; E = GCTT; F = CGCT; G = TGCC; H = ACTA. Backbone is a modified version of pSB1C3 with added SpeI site in front of gene, BsaI sites flanking, and 4bp fusion sites. See BBa_K783055.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Traci Haddock
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part was cloned off a BCD template from Sonya Iverson. Sonya Iverson based her designs for her BCD2 part off of a paper published by Mutalik, et al.
